thanks. Okay. I

28:53.306 --> 29:04.740
did a little checking in your 22, Longhorn. Did 
you? You noted that you were on the international

29:07.189 --> 29:10.272
stock judging team. Yes. I presume that was on your 
senior year? Yes. How did you become a member of

29:13.996 --> 29:15.598
that? By trying out for our, we had to, we'd take 
this livestock over here, and different barns,

29:16.399 --> 29:29.012
and they had hogs, beef cattle, horses, and sheep. 
And you'd have classes to place and give reasons

29:29.732 --> 29:34.137
on. Mr. Stangle, who was later dean out at Texas 
Tech, was our coach. And he'd grade you on your

29:40.708 --> 29:43.753
placings and on your greasings. And it was 
competitive. You got on there by competition. So

29:51.526 --> 29:55.353
how many of the students were on the team? Five. And 
each member, each one of each... did you

29:59.024 --> 30:01.788
specialize in one type of lifestyle? Everybody 
had to do all of them. Now when I was a fish,

30:06.075 --> 30:13.266
we had a freshman lifestyle judging contest at the 
end of the freshman year. And I looked out on that, I

30:14.688 --> 30:22.421
was high man of the freshman lifestyle judging 
contest and won a medal. And in 1920 I lost that

30:22.441 --> 30:24.524
medal. It was A.M. Walter medal. It was a hexagon 
shaped thing and I lost it in 1920. I did no work. In

30:34.676 --> 30:44.448
1940, 20 years later, we were going up to see our 
folks and we had a son at that time, nine years old.

30:45.028 --> 30:52.217
We stopped at Leonard's other store in Fort Worth 
and bought an iron gun for him to shoot when he went

30:45.028 --> 30:52.217
up there. So in Tuna, we lived on a city block and had 
a barn, an orchard and garden, chicken, all that

30:52.467 --> 31:00.806
kind of stuff. So he was out there in the lot looking 
for something to put up on the fence to shoot at and

31:00.826 --> 31:07.862
kicked up that metal. 20 years after I lost it.

